data.Name: Flora Adamian
data.Short_bio: Flora Adamian is a news and policy enthusiast from Los Angeles, CA. She previously worked as reporter in Berlin and LA, covering government policies (or lack thereof) and how they affect city residents.

data.Name: Ken Alvin
data.Short_bio: Retired senior manager and research scientist in computational science and high performance computing at a national laboratory. I had a great time working on the Data Entry team and getting a taste of the complexity and nuance in data assimilation and reporting across all of the states and territories. As an older person on the team, I have such great admiration and appreciation for the efforts of the students and early career professionals who volunteered so much time while juggling their work and family responsibilities. It gives me much optimism for the future, despite today’s challenges.

data.Name: Jesse Anderson
data.Short_bio: Jesse Anderson is an undergraduate student at the University of Maryland studying information science, data science, and global engineering leadership. She is a research assistant for the THAT lab, and within this position, she focuses on identifying how technologists can cultivate adaptive, accessible, and engaging information systems for people with dementia to help them address their information needs. She is also a Bluebonnet Data Fellow and enjoys applying data science techniques to a variety of sectors, such as health informatics, civic technology, and human-computer interaction.

data.Name: Sarah Anderson
data.Short_bio: I’m hoping to apply what I have experienced on CTP to the data science field to continue doing some good in the world.

data.Name: Alejandra Arevalo
data.Short_bio: Alejandra Arevalo is a Peruvian freelance journalist who graduated from NYU’s Arthur L. Carter Journalism Institute. At CTP, she worked in data entry and leading the Oral History Project which collected volunteer stories for posterity.

data.Name: Aryan
data.Short_bio: I am a high school student interested in Computer Science and Data Science. At CTP I did shifts in data entry and data quality as well as creating visualizations.

data.Name: Gowtham Asokan
data.Short_bio: Lead a team of students in automating data collection & quality checking for the Racial data tracker.

data.Name: Sonya Bahar
data.Short_bio: I'm a Professor of Biophysics at the University of Missouri at St. Louis. Being able to volunteer with CTP during this horrific year, to help with data entry, to provide accountability on racial health disparties and bear witness to the suffering in this country, was an honor and a privilege. To see this community come together in a time of crisis gave me hope that new things can spring from the ashes.

data.Name: Michael T. Barry Jr.
data.Short_bio: Michael T. Barry Jr. is a doctoral candidate in history at American University in Washington, DC. Michael is also a documentary filmmaker, specializing in oral history. His films “U Street Contested” and “The Universal Soldier: Vietnam” have won and been nominated for numerous awards, as they have screened at film festivals and historic venues across the country. He teaches American history at Montgomery College in Maryland. Follow him on Twitter at http://twitter.com/MTBarryJr.

data.Name: Travis Bartley
data.Short_bio: I'm a doctoral student and English instructor at the City University of New York, where I research language technology, media theory, and digital infrastructure. With CTP I worked with the Racial Data Tracker team to record demographic data on COVID rates.

data.Name: José Bayoán Santiago Calderón
data.Short_bio: Dr. Santiago Calderón is a postdoctoral research associate at the Biocomplexity Institute & Initiative of the University of Virginia. Bayoán is an economist by training specializing in methods, data science, and measurements.

data.Name: Jeanette Beebe
data.Short_bio: Jeanette Beebe is a journalist focused on tech, medicine, and health care. A reporter and editorial team member at The COVID Tracking Project, her reporting has appeared in TIME, The Daily Beast, Scientific American, Consumer Reports, NPR/WHYY, and Fast Company, where her article on health/medical data privacy was featured by the Aspen Institute's “Five Best Ideas of the Day.” She also writes a daily newsletter for Montclair State University’s Center for Cooperative Media. Her work as a freelance recordist/producer has been broadcast by the BBC, Gimlet Media, and NPR/ProPublica’s “Lost Mothers” series, which was a finalist for the Pulitzer Prize for Explanatory Reporting. She holds an A.B. in English from Princeton, and she served as an M.A. Scholar at NYU’s Science, Health, & Environmental Reporting Program. Born and raised in Iowa, she’s a long-time contributor to and advocate for literary communities.

data.Name: Ellen Berkovitch
data.Short_bio: Working journalist since the late 1980s, on beats including energy policy, western politics, arts and culture. Spent two decades in New Mexico as an investigative reporter and public radio news director producing long-form documentaries and running collaborative projects including coverage of Catholic church sex abuse scandal's impact in NM, and environmental pollution on Navajo Nation.  Now a visiting associate prof of journalism at Pratt Institute. At CTP worked with @KaraOehler on gaining access to Native American COVID data and developing systems for understanding discrepancies in state reporting on Native American populations. Was amazed by the organization and colleagueship of CTP's leadership and collaborators.

data.Name: Hannah Birch
data.Short_bio: I write and edit words and help make complex information more understandable. I also organize people and computers. I'm currently the content lead at the MTA in New York.

data.Name: Stanley Bishop
data.Short_bio: I am a Machine learning scientist specializing in microbial genomics, and as an early contributor to COVID-Tracking I largely stuck to my data-science Gopher roots.

data.Name: Kristian Bjørnard
data.Short_bio: Kristian Bjørnard is an Educator, Designer, Sustainabilitist, and Open-sourcerer based in Baltimore, MD. He works at the nexus of visual communication, the public domain, climate change, and technology. In his spare time Kristian dabbles in permaculture farming and attempts to make an old stone house, where he lives with his wife and two children, energy efficient.

data.Name: Libby Blazes
data.Short_bio: Current undergrad at Princeton University studying Ecology and Evolutionary Biology

data.Name: Danielle Bloch
data.Short_bio: I'm an infectious disease epidemiologist with a background in vector-borne and antimicrobial-resistant disease surveillance. I currently work at Kinsa Health, trying to build out an early warning system to prevent future outbreaks. At CTP, I helped get the Long-Term Care COVID Tracker off the ground and assisted with weekly LTC data entry.

data.Name: J. Albert Bowden II
data.Short_bio:
web developer specializing in front-end, a11y and dataops.
openness enthusiast.
ltc data team member.
dataops mostly around ltcf data.
wrote crosswalk between cms.gov nursing home dataset and ctp ltcf dataset.

data.Name: Rhea Boyd, MD, MPH
data.Short_bio: Dr. Rhea Boyd is a pediatrician, public health advocate and scholar who writes and teaches on the impacts of racism and inequity on health.

data.Name: Lauren Bradley
data.Short_bio: I'm Lauren Bradley! I work as a strategic partnerships professional in the non-profit sector. I am based in Los Angeles and love to spend time in the beautiful Cali outdoors -- hiking, camping, and soaking up the sun at the beach. I am so honored to have been a member of the COVID Tracking Project! Learning new skills and meeting new people, all while contributing to a national effort has been an experience I will be forever grateful for.

data.Name: Carol Brandmaier-Monahan
data.Short_bio: Carol is a former R&D Director at Bell Labs, from Randolph, NJ. At The COVID Tracking Project, she was shift lead for the COVID Racial Data Tracker (CRDT) and a member of the Data Entry and Community teams, where she led yearbook. For CRDT, Carol co-developed a python-based system to download race/ethnicity data automatically from state dashboards and created the State Grades Assessment Tool. Carol is grateful to be a part of the CTP community while bearing witness to the pandemic and is continually in awe at the smart, dedicated, fun, creative and empathetic people that make up this project.

data.Name: Eliot Brody
data.Short_bio: I am a journalist who is now venturing into the world of nonprofit communications. I was a reporter, watching press conferences, before joining the City Data team, where I helped compiled an initial spreadsheet of city data dashboards and collected data for several months on a number of counties in the Atlanta, Phoenix, and Portland metro areas.

data.Name: Mandy Brown
data.Short_bio: Mandy Brown is editorial lead at The COVID Tracking Project. She previously served as VP of Product at Vox Media.

data.Name: Kim Bryant
data.Short_bio: I lead strategy and operations for tech, media, and non-profits. As a team lead for CTP, I helped other team leads with strategy and ops planning, problem solving, and project management. I'm most proud of the work I did on the #wellbeing initiative, which provided CTP contributors with resources to support their biopsychosocial health and navigate secondary trauma from their work. My parents often describe their Peace Corps experience as one that gave them far more than they served others -- and I feel exactly the same about my time with CTP.

data.Name: Laura Bult
data.Short_bio: Video journalist currently at Vox.com, living in Brooklyn, NY.

data.Name: Sarah Burch
data.Short_bio:
Ops + Data @ Batch
former Ops + Data @ bitly

data.Name: Nicki Camberg
data.Short_bio: Hi! I had the honor of being CTP's City Data Manager, the Assistant Community Manager, helping write the weekly blog posts with the Editorial Team, and was our "emoji boss" and merch maker. As of now, I'm studying Political Science and Statistics at Barnard College with the hopes of going into journalism post-graduation. Being part of CTP made me feel like I was able to spend my pandemic doing valuable work that could help people - I don't have the training to be a doctor, I'm not a science whiz that can create a vaccine, and I'm not a policymaker - but I was able to be part of this project, and in doing so, played a part in informing the public and holding our government accountable. I have been consistently inspired and amazed by the hard work and passion of the people of CTP, and I will remember this experience for the rest of my life.

data.Name: Miriam Chappelka
data.Short_bio: Miriam Chappelka is a health data analyst. On the COVID Tracking Project, she analyzed and visualized racial disparities in years of life lost due to COVID.

data.Name: Ameera Chaudhry
data.Short_bio: I'm a DC-based healthcare analyst and helped with data entry at the COVID Tracking Project.

data.Name: Bharvi Chavre
data.Short_bio: Hi! My name is Bharvi and I am a Chemistry major on the pre-med track at Princeton University. On campus, I am a Peer Academic Advisor, Daily Princetonian Associate News Editor, and part of the USG Academic Committee.

data.Name: Charlie Cheever
data.Short_bio: I made some small code contributions to the API and website.

data.Name: Carl Chen

data.Name: Sylvia Cheng

At CTP, I helped with data entry and data quality projects, in which I closely observed how the pandemic impacted and hurt people deeply. My heart has never rested going through all these. I'm still trying to find ways in my research projects to better help vulnerable populations. When not thinking about health research, my brain is always occupied by eagerness to have a cat (still don't have one...).

data.Name: Marcie Cheung
data.Short_bio: Founder and CEO of KindMind, the only therapist matching solution built specifically to understand and help clinicians. At CTP, was part of the early team that refined the data entry and checking process.

data.Name: Hannah Cole

I studied chemistry in college and hope to attend medical school in the future. I contributed to the Data Entry team and enjoyed playing a small role in helping to get accurate and understandable data out to the larger public.

data.Name: Emily P Coles
data.Short_bio: I'm a ballroom dance teacher with a long-time interest in public health and social justice, and feel incredibly proud to have been part of the CTP Race Data entry team.

data.Name: Yoselin Coronado
data.Short_bio: I feel honored and proud to have been part of this project. Being part of The Covid Tracking Project was a great experience and one that will stay with me for the rest of my life.

data.Name: Jason Crane
data.Short_bio: I'm a team lead, a web developer and a former journalist just trying to help do some good in this world.

data.Name: Carol Cronin
data.Short_bio: Carol Cronin is a gerontologist with over twenty years experience working on health care issues—with a particular interest in consumer health information, aging, health care quality and patient safety.  She is Executive Director of a Maryland-based non-profit organization—the Informed Patient Institute (IPI)—whose mission is to ensure the public availability and use of actionable information about health care quality, patient safety and affordability to improve quality and lower costs.

data.Name: Hannah Cummins
data.Short_bio:
I graduated from ODU in 2019 with a BS in Biology and specific interest in entomology, vector borne disease, and epidemiology. I currently work for Public Health Command - Atlantic and want to pursue a PhD in Entomology.

I started working with CTP in March 2020 after teleworking left me with far too much free time. I started by doing press reporting for VA, DC, MD, and DE, joined LTC in May, City Data in June, as well as briefly worked with the Racial Data team. I am most proud of working with LTC and City Data, where I stayed to the ends of the projects.

data.Name: Artis Curiskis
data.Short_bio: Journalist and documentarian. Reporting & Outreach, Long-Term Care COVID Tracker and City Data Lead.

data.Name: Kate D'Anna
data.Short_bio: I was part of the volunteer team from Tank Design, supporting some of the website design effort.

data.Name: Natalie Dean
data.Short_bio: I am a biostatistician specializing in infectious disease epidemiology and vaccines. It was a pleasure to serve on the CTP Advisory Board and to observe the incredible achievements of this group. I am particularly proud of how well CTP has advocated for improving data quality, and for their work teaching the many, many consumers of their data sets how to use these responsibly.

data.Name: Katerina Dimitratos
data.Short_bio:
I'm the Chief Strategy Officer of a FinTech company and founder of Meddy Health. My career began with experience from PwC, Bloomberg, and S&P Global in data analysis, risk management, and strategy. 

Today, I'm building my own health tech startup (meddyhealth.co) and aiming to make a global societal impact using business as a force for good.

I joined the CTP on March 6, 2020 (the very beginning!) when I randomly sent a message to Alexis Madrigal offering to help with his "spreadsheet COVID tracker" at the time. The tracker grew into a project and the team later expanded to hundreds of volunteers across the country. I then shifted to assisting with state outreach and reporting.

data.Name: Ann Dinh
data.Short_bio: My professional interests are a blend of visual design, communication, and data within cultural industries. At CTP, I collected data for the COVID Racial Data Tracker, archived work in Data Quality, and was a general lurker in slack threads looking for random ways to help :)

data.Name: Geoff Donegan (Tank Design)
data.Short_bio: Geoff is Executive Creative Director at Tank Design, a Boston and San Francisco based brand and experience design agency.

data.Name: Wade Dorrell
data.Short_bio: I have a background in software engineering and healthcare data. I joined this project after identifying and reporting a few "bugs" in Idaho's early data reporting efforts - we got those fixed, but CTP helped ensure Idaho remained comparable to other states, accountable to its citizens and neighbors. I volunteered time doing "data entry" (collecting data from states' dashboards, feeding it into the data API) and providing feedback on that API.

data.Name: Caroline DuLaney
data.Short_bio: Caroline DuLaney works in the human rights field, leading genocide prevention and climate resilience programming at foundations and nonprofits.  In her time at CTP, she contributed to a data standards effort and worked closely with the reporting and outreach, long-term care, and CRDT teams.  She enjoys trail running in the Rocky Mountains.

data.Name: CJ Dunn
data.Short_bio:
I design typefaces for retail and custom clients through my type foundry, CJ Type. I enjoy both making type and using type, and am interested in the dialog between the two practices. 

At CTP I worked closely with Allen Tan to redesign the Data pages. I focused specifically on grid systems and typography.

data.Name: Mohini Dutta
data.Short_bio: I am a designer and illustrator from Brooklyn, I make games and experiences to explain complex systems to regular people. I collaborated with the CTP design and website teams to make an illustration representing the racial disparity in Covid-19. Thanks for having me!

data.Name: Larry Eason
data.Short_bio: For 36 years Larry has worked with organizations and leaders focused on making the world a better place. From nonprofits to foundations to social impact startups, Larry has a gift for helping change-makers tap the power of partnerships, technology, and innovation. Currently, Larry works as VP Strategic Partnerships at Catchafire, a social good company strengthening the nonprofit sector through scaled virtual capacity building. Larry is a strategic advisor to AerNos, a nanotech company focused on air pollution and climate gas monitoring, and ProSocial, a social impact consulting firm leveraging entertainment media as a key driver in culture shift and public engagement. Larry served as board chair of Healthy Child Healthy World, is a founding member of Children’s Hospital Los Angeles’ Digital Advisory Committee, and is a former USC Jesse Unruh Fellow. In late 2020 and early 2021, Larry provided pro bono assistance to the Covid Tracking Project, helping assemble a team of digital and communications experts to improve the website experience and to increase the reach and impact of the organization’s editorial. A surfer, potter, and painter, Larry lives in Pomona, CA with his wife, daughter, and many rescue animals.

data.Name: Laura Anne Edwards
data.Short_bio: NASA Datanaut, TED Resident, Buckminster Fuller Design Science Studio Resident, US State Dept. Advisory Committee for Technology & Innovation, /Public-Private Partnerships. I’m an Innovation Catalyst with a focus on open data infrastructure and systems thinking and a passion for space and interdisciplinary research.

data.Name: David Eik
data.Short_bio: I'm a recent graduate from Colorado College currently working in biomedical research. As someone who is interested in public health, virology, and science communication, I enjoyed working on CTP's reporting and data cities teams. I spent the majority of the summer of 2020 collecting daily case and death totals for cities in the Mid Atlantic region.

data.Name: Jess Engebretson
data.Short_bio: I'm a writer, teacher, and audio producer in New York City.  While my work is wide-ranging, I’m particularly interested in how people make sense of war, violence, and other painful histories. I am currently completing my doctorate in English and comparative literature at Columbia University, where my research focuses on the literature and reportage of the Nigeria-Biafra war. Previously, I worked for six years as a radio journalist in the US, Liberia, and South Sudan.

data.Name: Ana Estrada
data.Short_bio: My name is Ana Estrada and I work as a public school teacher in the state of Texas. I first became involved with The COVID Tracking Project back in March 2020 when schools shut down. I was especially interested in the Racial Data Tracker since I wanted to know how COVID was disproportionately affecting my students and their families.

data.Name: Jennifer Firehammer
data.Short_bio: I am a recent graduate from Purdue Nuclear Engineering, and I am planning to pursue a career as a physician. While volunteering for The COVID Tracking Project, I was a shift lead for the Data Entry team, and I will continue working with the Data Quality team to archive our processes and data. I am so thankful to have worked with the lovely group of volunteers here at CTP, and to have had the opportunity to provide reliable, transparent, and quality data on the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic in our country.

data.Name: Sydney Fishman
data.Short_bio: My name is Sydney Fishman and I have a master's in multimedia journalism from New York University. I have produced audio stories on immigration, the coronavirus pandemic, and mental health. My passion lies in reporting on immigration. At CTP, I researched southern states and the rise of coronavirus in states like Mississippi and Alabama. I am elated that I was able to volunteer with CTP, and I look forward to using our research in my future reporting.

data.Name: Amanda French
data.Short_bio: I began volunteering for The COVID Tracking Project March 18, 2020, helping to collect data and onboard volunteers. I used to run a lot of the morning data entry shifts back when we had morning shifts, and I'm now one of about 40 Shift Leads who takes turns running the daily afternoon data collection and publication shift. I created the training program for data entry volunteers, I organized volunteer swag, I manage Slack and G Suite accounts for CTP, and I run the Help Desk that tries to answer the many questions and data issues we get from the public. I've got a doctorate in English and have worked mostly in digital humanities throughout my career, notably as Coordinator for THATCamp, The Humanities and Technology Camp at the Roy Rosenzweig Center for History and New Media. I'm a long-time advocate for open access, open source, and open data. I live in Cary, North Carolina with my dog Darcy and my three cats.

data.Name: Robert Furberg
data.Short_bio: Robert Furberg is a Senior Clinical Informaticist at RTI International, where he studies how emerging technologies can be used for public health research. Throughout the COVID-19 pandemic, he has contributed to a range of efforts from presymptomatic disease detection, use of "Digital PPE," and standards development for population-level reporting and surveillance initiatives.

data.Name: WIlliam Gao
data.Short_bio: William is a student at Boston University who was a Data Science Intern at BU Spark! & Center for Antiracist Research, he was responsible for creating an automated data pipeline for the COVID Racial Data Tracker.

data.Name: Aviva Geiger Schwarz
data.Short_bio: Aviva Geiger Schwarz is a public health epidemiologist with experience in racial disparities research. Her role at the COVID Tracking Project included the presentation and analysis of COVID racial data. She also served as Data Editor for the COVID Racial Data Tracker at Boston University's Center for Antiracist Research.

data.Name: Rowan Moore Gerety
data.Short_bio: I'm a print + audio journalist in Phoenix. I worked with a handful of mid/western states—Montana, North Dakota, South Dakota, Arizona, Wyoming, and Nebraska—to clarify data definitions and make more robust information about COVID-19 available on their public-facing dashboards.

data.Name: Rachel Glickhouse
data.Short_bio: I'm a journalist and collaborations leader. I helped with impact tracking, project management, outreach, public training sessions and other editorial projects.

data.Name: Alice Goldfarb
data.Short_bio: Alice Goldfarb led the COVID Racial Data Tracker, working with phenomenal colleagues to compile, categorize, and analyze the race and ethnicity COVID-19 data from states. She is a Nieman Visiting Fellow, where she is developing guidance for understanding and reporting on demographic data about public health.

data.Name: Anika Govil
data.Short_bio: Anika joined the COVID-19 project in November 2020. Since then, she has worked on the data entry and data quality team! She has enjoyed her team with the COVID Tracking Project and is so thankful to have gotten the opportunity to take part in the wonderful initiative!

data.Name: Lou Hamann

data.Name: Chase Harrington

data.Name: Lauran Hazan
data.Short_bio: I'm a software product manager, experience with data and IoT, especially in the healthcare delivery and medical device areas. I got to do different things at CTP - from helping with daily data publication and cracking the mysteries of probable case definitions and helping support data visualization.

data.Name: Randall Helms
data.Short_bio: I am a data professional by trade, leading the data team at a subsidiary of Commerzbank (Germany’s second biggest bank), and in the first few months of at the project I contributed some data sets and code for working pulling and manipulating relevant additional contextual data sets from the US Census, the Kaiser Family Foundation and the CDC on topics like demographic characteristics at state and county level, historical hospital bed availability, and historical flu data (mortality and trends).

data.Name: Justin Hendrix
data.Short_bio: I work in media and technology. For a year I reported on New York's covid data.

data.Name: Kragh Hertel
data.Short_bio: I am a retired Software and Systems Engineer, and Engineering Manager, glad to be able to volunteer and contribute with my time and skills.

data.Name: Leslie Heyison
data.Short_bio: Design market research studies end-to-end for health care and pharmaceuticals clients including strategic goal setting, study design, moderation-interviews, final reports and key takeaways.  See LinkedIn for details.

data.Name: Claire Heyison
data.Short_bio: Claire Heyison is a health policy researcher by day and has been thrilled to be able to contribute to the COVID Tracking Project's Racial Data Trcacker by night. Her research spans a range of topics,  including health care payment and delivery reform, pharmaceutical policy, immigrant health, and LGBTQ+ health.

data.Name: Matt Hilliard
data.Short_bio: Originally a software engineer, today Matt is a product manager at a technology company in the Washington, D.C. area who also occasionally reviews novels on his blog and for the magazine Strange Horizons.

data.Name: Hannah Hoffman

data.Name: Sarah Hofmann

data.Name: Jacqueline Houtman
data.Short_bio: I have a PhD in Medical Microbiology and Immunology from UW-Madison, where I studied the immune response to a mouse coronavirus. I now work as a freelance biomedical writer/editor. I have published two books for young readers, The Reinvention of Edison Thomas (a novel) and Troublemaker for Justice (a biography of Bayard Rustin, with coauthors Walter Naegle and Michael G. Long). It was an honor to work with this wonderful community on both data entry and science communication.  Speak truth to power!

In my free time, I dabble in fiction writing, drawing, and getting absorbed into the internet.

data.Name: Noah Jacobson
data.Short_bio: An avid runner with an interest for improving public health and education

data.Name: Will Jaw

data.Name: Jaclyn Jeffrey-Wilensky

data.Name: Glen Johnson

I'm probably best known for running our All Hands meetings for all of our volunteers.

data.Name: Alex Johnson

data.Name: Stann-Omar Jones
data.Short_bio:
I’m a trilingual business operations specialist and trained political scientist within the impact sector. In my career, I have contributed to the success of over 80 entrepreneurial startups across sectors such as mobile technology, urban innovation, and financial inclusion and helped raise millions in funds to bolster democracy in Syria and the Middle East. 

Within CTP, I helped co-build and maintain one of the largest publicly available COVID-19 datasets in the country by working with a cross-functional team of scientists, journalists, reporters, developers, engineers, and federal/local officials. I inputted, cleansed, standardized, documented, and annotated data to spot inconsistencies and provide a deeper understanding and contextualization of the ethno-demographic impact and trends of COVID-19 nationwide.

data.Name: Kedar Joyner
data.Short_bio: I'm a UX/UI designer and web developer who loves to design and build software that contributes to the greater good. I joined the COVID Tracking Project in October 2020 as a design/dev volunteer, and worked alongside an amazing crew on website projects for the Racial Data Tracker.

data.Name: Sarah Kahl

data.Name: Ryan Kailath

data.Name: Evangelos Kassos

data.Name: John Keefe

data.Name: Pat Kelly

data.Name: Deirdre Kennedy

data.Name: Noah Kim
data.Short_bio: I study neuroscience at Princeton University and love everything to do with data. data.Name: Samuel J Klein
data.Short_bio: wikisourceror; {{cn}}; stress-testing knowledge futures.

data.Name: Elliott Klug
data.Short_bio: In my professional career, I have worked in a number of industries performing many roles but I always find myself drawn back to data and spreadsheets. A true jack-of-all-trades, I was in the perfect place and time to join the CTP team helping in the data entry process. It has been a defining experience in my life being on this team of high-performing volunteers and I am honored to have been a part of it.

data.Name: Julia Kodysh
data.Short_bio: I am a computational researcher working on personalized cancer vaccines. In my not-very-past life, I was a data and infrastructure engineer at big and small organizations. At CTP, I'm a Data Infrastructure co-lead.

data.Name: Diana Kruzman
data.Short_bio: Diana is a freelance journalist writing at the intersection of the environment, urban issues and international affairs. She is currently finishing up her master's degree at New York University and has previously written for Bedford + Bowery, LAist, Los Angeleno, Religion News Service, the GroundTruth Project and Earther. Follow her on Twitter @DKruzman.

data.Name: Maggie Kubicek
data.Short_bio: Journalism Student at New York University.

data.Name: Olivier Lacan
data.Short_bio: Olivier is a Paris-born French software engineer and open source software contributor. He works in online interactive technology education under a work visa in Orlando, Florida. Olivier was an early data entry and website contributor with The COVID Tracking Project. He later transitioned to focus exclusively on Florida data access issues with local journalists, data scientists, and epidemiologists. He co-wrote an extensive CTP blog post with the amazing Rebecca Glassman analyzing Florida COVID-19 data issues in July 2020.

data.Name: Jess Ladd
data.Short_bio: Jess Ladd is a serial social entrepreneur with a background in infectious disease epidemiology. Most recently, she founded and led the nonprofit Callisto which creates tech to support sexual assault survivors and detect repeat sexual offenders.

data.Name: Betsy Ladyzhets
data.Short_bio: Betsy Ladyzhets is a data journalist and science writer based in Brooklyn, New York. She runs the COVID-19 Data Dispatch, an independent publication providing news and resources on tracking the pandemic. She’s also a research associate at Stacker and a member of the National Association of Science Writers.

data.Name: Jennifer Larsen
data.Short_bio:
MSIS Graduate Student at University of South Florida

I contemporaneously collect Florida's vital statistics data that no one really asked for, but everyone really needs (they just don't know it yet!) I also collected the year end data for New Jersey and Ohio.

data.Name: Camille Le
data.Short_bio: My name is Camille and I'm from the Bay Area in California. I enjoy reading, cooking and volunteering.

data.Name: Jeremy Lederman
data.Short_bio: I study Industrial and Systems Engineering at Virginia Tech, with minors in Business, Statistics, and Creative Writing. I was a rising senior going into 2021, but I decided to postpone my graduation by a year to add a third minor, take part time classes, and intern. I volunteered with the Data Entry Intake team during my time with the CTP. It was so great to be part of the team that was so essential to informing the public of the state of the pandemic, and It was really cool for my Dad, who uses CTP's info daily, to see that I contributed to this!

data.Name: Brian S.-K. Li
data.Short_bio: I'm an undergraduate student at Princeton University. Since joining CTP in May 2020, I've worked as a Data Entry and Data Quality Shift Lead. I've had the privilege of meeting many wonderfully kind and talented teammates over 400+ shifts, and I'm incredibly grateful to have had an opportunity to contribute to CTP's work.

data.Name: E Rosalie Li-Rodenborn
data.Short_bio: E Rosalie is an interdisciplinary scholar at the Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health with a variety of interests: science policy, health security (public health + national security), and disinformation. She cultivates a range of experiences, and in the past year contributed to the HIT-COVID study published by Nature, volunteered on the Covid Tracking Project at The Atlantic, team-wrote a policy memo published in the Journal of Science Policy and Governance, and started a disinformation database called Hoaxlines via her science communication project, NOVEL SCIENCE. To follow her work, subscribe to NovelScience.Substack.com.

data.Name: Jocelyn Limas
data.Short_bio: Hi! I just graduated from UCLA with a B.S. in Psychobiology and a minor in Evolutionary Medicine, and I will be going back to UCLA to obtain my MPH in Epidemiology. I worked as part of Data Entry as a Data Doublechecker during my time at CTP and will always be grateful to work on such a wonderful project!

data.Name: Daniel Lin
data.Short_bio: Daniel is a student at Dartmouth College, majoring in Sociology and Music. In addition to listening to stories and meeting new people, Daniel loves :party-possum: and using the :sweat_smile: emoji reaction.

data.Name: Asia Lindsay
data.Short_bio: Born in Hong Kong, schooled at Oxford, Asia is a former digital nomad who has lived in eight countries, and traveled to >90, learning languages as she goes. Now settled in the UK, Asia builds community at Google for Education and Google for Startups, with a heavy emphasis on diversity and inclusion programming. Prior to this, she championed community at TED and Sandbox. In her free time, she volunteers at Wikitongues, Blix Network and as Director of Community for the COVID Tracking Project.

data.Name: Zach Lipton
data.Short_bio: Zach is a San Francisco software developer. As Data Infrastructure co-lead, he helped build tools to manage and store the Project's data. He can't imagine a better group of people to have spent the pandemic with.

data.Name: Tatiana Mac
data.Short_bio: I'm a American software engineer who focuses on creating ethical, accessible, and performant products. I primarily collaborated on architecture and design of the Racial Data Tracker and supported the engineers with accessibility improvements.

data.Name: Sharon Machlis
data.Short_bio: I pitched in at the beginning to help with Massachusetts and other data updates until the project create its own scraper. I'm the director of editorial data & analytics at IDG Communications and an R enthusiast. Still provide weekly Covid data updates to my local community. My husband lost his mother to Covid in April (2020).

data.Name: Ramla Mahmood
data.Short_bio: Ramla Mahmood is a product design manager based in DC. She contributed to the early designs of the website.

data.Name: Ethan Marcotte
data.Short_bio: Ethan is an independent designer who helps organizations create sites and services that can be accessed by everyone, everywhere. Notably, he introduced the world to responsive web design.

data.Name: JD Maresco
data.Short_bio: I’m a cofounder @ Citizen and the Founder & CEO @ Batch. I helped build the data, IT, and operational infrastructure for the organization as it rapidly scaled and supported the launch of our advisory board.

data.Name: Mat “Wilto” Marquis
data.Short_bio: When not making fast, accessible, responsive websites, Mat “Wilto” Marquis is a former amateur boxer, aspiring chef, halfway decent carpenter, barely passable antique British motorcycle mechanic, and wannabe botanist. He keeps busy.

data.Name: Michal Mart
data.Short_bio:
I am a battle-tested technical leader, having served in leadership roles at startups, consulting companies and large corporations. Many of these roles involved remotely coordinating geographically disparate teams, which was good preparation for CTP.

At CTP I started and co-lead the Data Quality team for the TACO (testing and outcomes) data. The people at CTP are so special and made this the best work experience of my life -- I am so grateful to have met and worked with all of you!

data.Name: Barb Mattscheck
data.Short_bio: Retired corporate librarian specializing in product information management, media asset management, taxonomy creation, and metadata normalization. Started computing with punchcards and communicating via acoustic coupler and now work in the cloud!

data.Name: Kyong Mazzaro
data.Short_bio: I am a political science PhD candidate and Data for Public Good fellow at the Graduate Center, CUNY. I study elections, violence, and media freedom. At CTP, I was part of the data entry team for the Racial Data Tracker.

data.Name: Sarah R. McLaughlin
data.Short_bio: I'm a volunteer at the COVID Tracking Project supporting various data visualization and analytic projects, mostly within the long-term-care team. I have a background in Epidemiology/Biostatistics and am currently working at a Boston-based SaaS company.

data.Name: Elijah Merrett
data.Short_bio: Educator, lifelong learner, and design enthusiast based in the Southeast.

data.Name: Karen Merritt
data.Short_bio: Karen Merritt is a downeast Maine-based writer, artist and community health advocate. When she's not working on writing or art projects and thinking about community engagement, Karen works as an environmental and public health engineer and engineering instructor.

data.Name: Robinson Meyer
data.Short_bio: Robinson Meyer is a staff writer at The Atlantic and a cofounder of the COVID Tracking Project. He’s also a visiting fellow in journalism at the Energy Policy Institute at the University of Chicago. He lives in Washington, D.C.

data.Name: Olivia  Meyers
data.Short_bio: I am a senior, pre-med biology student at Princeton University. In my sparse free time, I like to run, find new parks and hikes, and reading fiction out loud with friends.

data.Name: Theo Michel
data.Short_bio: Theo is a long-time software geek and project manager, and loves using technology to do cool things and help people. As a project manager at CTP, he worked to coordinate efforts among teams, with a focus on data quality.

data.Name: Kevin Miller
data.Short_bio: Website Team Lead. Mountain saunterer, canyon explorer, wave tumbler, bike rider, trail loser, sometime computer starer.

data.Name: Emily E. N. Miller
data.Short_bio: I am a doctoral candidate in Population Studies and Social Policy at Princeton University. I received a B.S. in Policy Analysis and Management and minored in Inequality Studies at Cornell University. Prior work in the health field includes studying health communication and drunk driving. I also conducted field research about community health in rural Kentucky. It was great to contribute in a small way to this massive data collection and public health endeavor. Thanks to everyone involved in CTP!

data.Name: Neil Miller
data.Short_bio: I'm an analyst and researcher for mission-driven organizations. I'm grateful to have played a role in helping CTP fulfill its vision -- providing clear, accurate information for people in the face of a pandemic that's too fast-moving and massive to truly understand. Its power in arming the public with information has inspired me to adopt the open-data model for my own projects.

data.Name: Monica Monroe
data.Short_bio: I'm Monica! I'm a creative! I'm someone who's always up for a challenge! I love bringing ideas to life, and I love collaborating with others who do the same.

data.Name: Simon Morrow
data.Short_bio: I'm a former physicist, current science writer. I did data entry at CTP for both the core data entry team and the long-term care team.

data.Name: Catherine M. Mullaly, MD FRCPC MPH MS
data.Short_bio: Dr. Mullaly is an attending MD anesthesiologist at Massachusetts Eye and Ear, and Instructor in Anesthesia at Harvard Medical School, in Boston, MA. She completed an MPH in Global Health from the Harvard T. H. Chan School of Public Health (HSPH) in 2010, and an MS in Journalism from the Columbia Journalism School in 2015. The title of her 2010 HSPH MPH thesis was: "Ventilator Allocation During Pandemic Influenza: Is the Institute of Medicine 2009 disaster triage algorithm justified on a scientific and ethical basis?" Her volunteer CTP work focused on population data visualization and state data reporting standards. Follow along @MullalyMD.

data.Name: Mike Murphy
data.Short_bio: I work in Cybersecurity for the US Government and was so glad to be able to help out my fellow humans doing data collection work for CTP.

data.Name: Lindsay Muscato
data.Short_bio: Editor and writer, lover of collaborative projects. It was a joy to be even a small part of this incredibly huge lift of a project, filled with brilliant humans who formed this vibrant community in a time of such need.

data.Name: Vishnu R Nair
data.Short_bio: Philosopher. Poet. Programmer.

data.Name: Soham Nanavati
data.Short_bio: Sophomore at UNC-Chapel Hill with an intent to pursue a BSPH in Biostatistics. Aspiring physician and epidemiologist.

data.Name: Jeffrey Ndubisi
data.Short_bio: Student at Columbia University with a 702 area code. Happy to have helped this yearlong effort.

data.Name: Quang P. Nguyen
data.Short_bio: I am currently a Ph.D. candidate in the Quantitative Biomedical Sciences Program at Dartmouth College. My work primarily focuses on statistical methods for finding associations between infant gut microbiomes and early life exposures. Joining The COVID Tracking Project has been a life-changing moment for me. Every day I am humbled and awed at the collective smart-ness of everyone, of whom I am grateful to be around.

data.Name: Duy Nguyen
data.Short_bio: Duy Nguyen is in his senior year at New York University, studying data science and journalism.

data.Name: Gabe O'Leary
data.Short_bio: Software engineer & lover of data viz who found himself with too much free time and a need for a creative outlet as the project was beginning.

data.Name: Kara Oehler
data.Short_bio: Kara Oehler co-leads the Outreach & Reporting team at the COVID Tracking Project, the City Data team and the Long-Term-Care COVID Tracker.

data.Name: Dayo Paul Oluwakoya
data.Short_bio: My works mirror African diaspora to the world. Kindly visit http://www.newswatchnigeria.com for more of me. My prowess in data tracking and digital multimedia skills make news consumption interesting and factual.

data.Name: Judith P. Oppenheim
data.Short_bio: PhD Process Development Engineer, Poet, and Pianist.  1978 BS Math Sciences and Chemical Engineering, Rice U; 1983 PhD Chemical Engineering, U of Houston. Also passionate about Texas Data.  Live in Friendswood just outside of Houston having also spent years in:  Pensacola, Chicago, and Tulsa.  Native of El Paso.  13 Patents and 3 State Fair Bread Baking Ribbons.  Married to Photographer Bruce K. Blackwell.

data.Name: Roberto Orellana
data.Short_bio:
Dr. Orellana is a social and behavioral scientist at the University of Washington. His work on HIV prevention with racial/ethnic and sexual minorities throughout the Americas led him and colleagues to respond to the COVID-19 pandemic early on by organizing community responses in tribal communities in the U.S and Latin America. Dr. Orellana contributed to the collection and dissemination of data showing from the very beginning of the pandemic the impact of COVID-19 on Indigenous and Latinx communities in the U.S.

Selected Dissemination Products:

COVID-19 Cases Among American Indian/Alaska Natives
https://medium.com/@robertoorellana_57833/covid-19-cases-among-american-indian-alaska-natives-as-of-04-29-2020-bb9263f76ed3

Native Americans in New Mexico Experience Multiple Epidemics, COVID-19 is the latest addition.
https://medium.com/@robertoorellana_57833/native-americans-in-new-mexico-experience-multiple-epidemics-covid-19-is-the-latest-addition-eabd7bd7638c

COVID-19 Among Latinos in Oregon: Another epidemic finds an environment of risk where Latinos get hit hard from all directions.
https://medium.com/@robertoorellana_57833/covid-19-another-epidemic-finds-an-environment-of-risk-in-oregon-where-latinos-get-hit-hard-from-4950e4e7aed

data.Name: Daria Orlowska
data.Short_bio: Daria is a Data Librarian and Assistant Professor at Western Michigan University. She began volunteering at CTP in November, and since then has helped out with data entry and an assortment of data quality tasks.

data.Name: Rick Palmer
data.Short_bio: First and foremost my biggest passion is working with data in its many forms. Data pulling, cleanup, organizing, charting and more. At CTP I performed research and reported data, designed automated and semi-automated spreadsheets using Google Apps Script, function, formulas and more. Also perform freelance data and spreadsheet work.

data.Name: Ryan Panchadsaram
data.Short_bio: A public crisis requires a unified public response. A unified public response requires public data. Joined CTP to help inform the public and keep our governments accountable.

data.Name: Brandon Park
data.Short_bio:
Brandon leads the Data Entry team, outside of being the primary CTP-wide emoji fodder. 

He is forever indebted to the many volunteers that donated time and effort to the cause of tracking COVID data on a daily basis. 

Secretly he was easyDC the whole time.

data.Name: Isha Pasumarthi
data.Short_bio: I am an undergraduate student and aspiring pediatrician passionate about healthcare advocacy, disease prevention, and eliminating disparities in health. Since joining The COVID Tracking Project in May 2020, I have had the incredible honor of doing outreach to state health officials in Indiana, Maine, and Washington as well as CRDT and LTC data entry. It has been such a joy and privilege to work alongside incredible trailblazers and spend my pandemic year doing such timely and historic work.

data.Name: Shreyas Pasumarthi
data.Short_bio:
From building my own computer in the eighth grade to working with start-ups on machine learning algorithms, STEM has always been a vehicle for my passions for technology and creativity. Now, I work with non-profits, start-ups, and volunteer organizations to translate my creativity and passion for technology into concrete philanthropic efforts.

At CTP, I visualized the disparate effects of COVID-19 on minorities using CTP's Racial Data Set and Tableau. I also created a graphic that shows cases and deaths per 100,000 people by race or ethnicity for Data 4 Black Lives.

data.Name: Katherine Paur
data.Short_bio: Kathy runs Marin Math Circle and teaches math at the Nueva School in California.  Previously she completed a PhD in math at Harvard with a focus on modeling infectious diseases, and ran the modeling and analysis group for Kiva Systems (now Amazon Robotics).  During the pandemic, she taught Infectious Disease Dynamics and Modeling remotely at the North Carolina School of Science and Math.  Kathy ran data entry shifts for the COVID Tracking Project from March 2020 to March 2021.

data.Name: Joanna Pearlstein
data.Short_bio: Joanna Pearlstein is a journalist in San Francisco whose work has appeared in WIRED, the New York Times, the Atlantic, and the Washington Post.

data.Name: David Phillips
data.Short_bio: I'm an Edtech professional who came in very late to CTP, but I am proud of the shifts I was able to do. It was a real honor to play even a small role in such an extraordinary and necessary project.

data.Name: Catherine C. Pollack
data.Short_bio: Catherine C. Pollack is a PhD Candidate and NIH-Dartmouth Big Data to Knowledge Fellow in the Quantitative Biomedical Sciences Program at Dartmouth College. She received her BS with High Distinction from the University of Virginia with a double major in biomedical engineering and applied statistics (engineering concentration). Catherine's dissertation work leverages machine learning and natural language processing to quantify the characteristics and spread of public health misinformation on social media. Outside of her dissertation, Catherine is a collaborator within the COVID-19 Dispersed Volunteer Research Network, a statistical consultant with the Dartmouth-Hitchcock Biostatistics Collaboration Core, and a graduate peer tutor with the Dartmouth Center for Research, Writing, and Information Technology. Within the COVID Tracking Project, Catherine has conducted data analysis for the Data Cities team and HHS Hospitalization project and worked with the Science Communications team to develop "Epidemiology 101" presentations, contribute to the Weekly Updates, and review miscellaneous content for scientific accuracy.

data.Name: L Michael Posey
data.Short_bio: Being a native of southwestern Georgia, I noticed early in the pandemic how important the data were in conveying the dire situation emerging in the Albany, Ga., area. Per capita, more cases and deaths were occurring in this area than in New York, even though the actual numbers were small. I found the COVID Tracking Project website needed, valuable, and helpful.

data.Name: Divya Ramjee
data.Short_bio: Divya Ramjee is a Ph.D. candidate and adjunct professor in American University’s Department of Justice, Law and Criminology. She is also a Senior Fellow at the Center for Security, Innovation, and New Technology and a Researcher in the COVID-19 Dispersed Volunteer Research Network.

data.Name: Prajakta Ranade
data.Short_bio:
I began volunteering for The COVID Tracking Project March 8th, 2020, mainly to help with data collection. Initially since team was pretty small a lot of us got a chance to help with and build various parts of the project. I primarily worked and lead our data entry team until Oct 2020. As Data Entry team lead, I have done multiple shifts for data collection and publication and worked on schedule optimization and other process improvements. I was also responsible for developing initial iteration and ongoing maintenance of State Grades project. State grades has been an important tool for our reporting and outreach teams and was key driver in greater data transparency from the states.

I am a registered dietitian and live and work in San Francisco Bay Area. For me, the time I got to spend at CTP with the amazing team of volunteers has pretty much been the difference between a pandemic year wasted and a pandemic year well spent.

data.Name: Rebma
data.Short_bio:
An infrastructure engineer who likes puzzles, solving problems and automating life. CTP was a humbling and educational experience from which Rebma learned a lot about work processes, remote work and collaboration, and of course, the utter importance of emojis on Slack.
Rebma was the comic-relief in an otherwise very professional environment.

Likes TACOs and avocados.

data.Name: Nicole S. Rivera
data.Short_bio: Nicole's career has focused on developing creative and strategic ways to communicate complex issues with clarity to persuasively move legislation, close deals and partnerships, and influence public policy.

data.Name: Jasna Rodulfa-Blemberg
data.Short_bio: I am a humanities graduate-turned-software engineer who has worked in the government, non-profit, EdTech, and healthcare sectors. I primarily write in Scala, so adjusting to the Gatsby framework and brushing up on my JavaScript for the CTP was a challenge! I created initial versions of a couple of graphs for the Racial Data Tracker, as well as add some minor improvements to the website's RSS feed.

data.Name: GG Rowe
data.Short_bio:
I have a bachelors degree in computer science and mathematics and a PMP certified project management professional.  I'm a career IT Professional working with software applications doing large enterprise implementations and support as a project manager and department manager.  
For CTP, I helped the effort to develop the process for the external support desk, began the effort, and lead the members on the team.  I also assisted with data entry.

data.Name: Emma Rubin
data.Short_bio: Emma Rubin is a 2020 graduate from Mount Holyoke College pursuing a career in data journalism.

data.Name: Stacey Rupolo
data.Short_bio: As a recovering photojournalist pursuing a master's in social work, I joined the CTP in March of 2020 because it felt like the best way to put my journalism training to good use. In my time working on the project, I helped launch the Racial Data Tracker and Long-Term-Care Data sets.

data.Name: Aarushi Sahejpal
data.Short_bio: Aarushi is the deputy lead for long-term care at the COVID Tracking Project. She also studies International Relations and Data Science at American University, in Washington D.C.

data.Name: Micaela Sandoval
data.Short_bio: Micaela Sandoval, MPH is an infectious disease epidemiologist and PhD student, focusing on emerging infectious diseases, health equity, and global health

data.Name: Jason Santa Maria
data.Short_bio:
I'm an accomplished design leader with over 20 years of experience leading diverse and multidisciplinary teams in product, media, marketing, and branding.

I created the CTP logo and brand package. I also collaborated on early designs for the website, and typography and color palettes for data visualization.

data.Name: Kara Schechtman
data.Short_bio: Kara co-leads the data quality team of The COVID Tracking Project.  In the fall, she'll be starting an MS in Symbolic Systems at Stanford University as a Knight-Hennessy scholar.

data.Name: Grant Schechtman
data.Short_bio: I am a student at Wesleyan University who volunteered in Data Entry at CTP! Thank you to my amazing sister, Kara, for getting me involved in CTP!

data.Name: Anna Schmidt
data.Short_bio: I'm a software engineer at Tesla from Michigan, now living in Seattle, WA. In my free time I foster cats and enjoy exercise of any form. I'm honored to have worked on many aspects of the Covid Tracking Project, from data entry to answering emails and state assessments, with the other incredible volunteers.

data.Name: Ryan Scholl
data.Short_bio: Ryan Scholl is a digital marketing professional by day and a hiker, photographer, and National Parks aficionado in his spare time. He is grateful to have had to opportunity to contribute to the COVID Tracking Project.

data.Name: Andrew Schwartz
data.Short_bio: I am a software engineer and student. In March 2020, I started volunteering with the COVID Tracking Project. Until March 2021, I worked on the covidtracking.com website with a focus on communicating racial data to the public.

data.Name: Nathan Selikoff
data.Short_bio: Nathan has been programming and making art since he was a little kid, sitting at a Commodore 64 staring at that blinking cursor - the pulse of possibility. He loves bringing interactive experiences to life, playing music with friends, gardening, and fermenting all the things. Nathan and his wife Amy live in sunny Orlando, Florida with their snuggly cat Olive, but travel the world whenever they get the chance.

data.Name: Matthias Shapiro
data.Short_bio: Matthias is a software developer and data visualization enthusiast who is grateful that he was able to have some small part in the Covid Tracking Project.

data.Name: Brandon Shaw
data.Short_bio: I am a Junior at Bishop Gorman High School where I serve as Vice President of our Black Student Union chapter; selected by our Dean as an Ambassador for our school's Gael2Gael program to mentor incoming students; a member of National Honors Society, Spanish Honors Society and Rho Kappa Social Studies Honors Society; and a highly ranked Men's Varsity Tennis Player. Outside of school, I spend my time involved with research and volunteer work for underrepresented groups that are impacted by social inequalities. For example I have been a volunteer for The Covid Tracking Project (CTP) since June of 2020 starting as a data tracker and then promoting to race data tracking where I tracked Covid case information by state which was published nationally. The CTP empowered me to be a part of a dynamic team and allowed me to flourish and taught me firsthand that someone like myself can make a difference to a goal bigger than myself, even at 16 years of age. I am also a teen panelist for our local hip hop radio station Power 88.1 where we get the teens talking each week on the air about issues our community faces and we recognize black excellence. I have a particular interest in conducting more research on the social inequalities for education in my state, where Nevada is ranked last in the country for education.

data.Name: Dr. Lindsey N. Shultz
data.Short_bio: I'm a physician and public health analyst originally from Pittsburgh, whose interests from pre-COVID times include harms reduction, drug policy, and health systems.  Working on science communication at CTP has been the pleasure of a lifetime- as has been watching a group of clever, lovely, dedicated people use radical compassion and transparency as a means of documenting the trajectory of a pandemic- and providing a living example of what the scientific process can be.

data.Name: Jill Shumann
data.Short_bio: Jill Shumann was most recently the Vice President for Francophone and Lusophone Africa at Population Services International (PSI), where she was responsible for all aspects of eight country programs implementing HIV, malaria, reproductive health, and sanitation projects. Jill also worked at PSI from 1996 to 2007, holding various roles including Country Representative (Mozambique) Regional Director, and Vice President.  Between the two experiences at PSI, she worked domestically in family homelessness and domestic violence, focusing on fundraising, marketing, and volunteer management.  She was also a self-employed consultant in global health, performing a range of programmatic roles. Jill has two master’s degrees from Johns Hopkins University: in International Affairs and in International Public Health. Jill was also a Peace Corps Volunteer in Guinea, West Africa.

data.Name: Sara Simon
data.Short_bio: Sara Simon began her journalism career as a web developer at Vermont Public Radio. She later worked as a software engineer at The New York Times and as an investigative data reporter with Spotlight PA. In September 2020, Sara joined The COVID Tracking Project to help with data quality efforts, and in the fall of 2021, she'll be heading to graduate school to study the history of U.S. government technology.

data.Name: Samantha Steiner
data.Short_bio: I am a current junior studying Human Nutrition, Food and Exercise at Virginia Tech. I am on the Pre Physician Assistant track and have had experience in several medical settings. I participated in the data entry section of the COVID Tracking Project and felt so rewarded after each shift I completed. I am so thankful to the COVID Tracking Project for allowing me to expand my knowledge in the healthcare field and meet such amazing people!

data.Name: Tom Subak
data.Short_bio: I am a digital transformer who had the honor and privilege of working with Alexis, Erin, and Kevin on the refresh of the covidtracking.com site.

data.Name: Ruirui Sun
data.Short_bio: I had a background of PhD in Economics, with research focus on healthcare cost, efficiency and IT adoption. After graduation I worked at the HHS as an economist, analyzing the US hospitalization data.

data.Name: Ganda Suthivarakom
data.Short_bio: I am an editor and writer based in Los Angeles, CA. Doing CTP data entry gave me a sense of civic purpose and understanding when I needed it most. Thank you to everyone I learned from.

data.Name: Allen Tan
data.Short_bio: Allen Tan is an editorial designer at ProPublica. As the design lead at The Covid Tracking Project, he helped make the first version of the website and later redesigns, including an overhaul of the display of national and state data.

data.Name: Mary K. Taylor
data.Short_bio: Mary Taylor holds a degree in Information Science from the University of Texas at Austin and is a Returned Peace Corps Volunteer who served in the Caribbean/Latin America. Her day job is working for the State of California as a Business and IT Analyst on assignment to the COVID-19 pandemic and California's wildfire season.

data.Name: Meghan Testerman
data.Short_bio: Meghan Testerman (she/her) is the behavioral sciences librarian at Princeton University. She strives to keep the university's informal motto, 'In the nation's service and in the service of humanity,' at the heart of all her professional and volunteer work.

data.Name: Erika Thomson
data.Short_bio: I am a sophomore Industrial Engineering student at Texas A&M, and I'm fascinated by the stories data can tell when the numbers are presented in in a clear and truthful way. I joined the COVID Tracking Project in May 2020 and spent most of my time volunteering with the Data Quality team where I worked on finding, interpreting, and recording data definitions.

data.Name: Dylan Thurston
data.Short_bio: Professor of Mathematics at Indiana University, Bloomington

data.Name: Eric Topol, MD
data.Short_bio: Professor, Molecular Medicine, Scripps Research; practicing physician (cardiology)

data.Name: Blake Truitt
data.Short_bio: I am a development consultant helping non-profits raise philanthropic funding and partnership revenue. In my previous role managing The Atlantic's relationships with private foundations, I had the pleasure of working with Alexis to secure early grant funding of CTP.

data.Name: Toph Tucker
data.Short_bio: I’ve made charts for a few different jobs and volunteered as soon as I heard about the project in March; I was scared and cooped up in an unfamiliar place and it was profoundly therapeutic to channel the desperation. I had like the tiniest possible role, I only ever made a few charts and ran a skillshare and then got overwhelmed again by my “real job”. But it was a joy and a salve to watch everyone else. I know this sounds hokey but I swear it is the most impressive organizational effort (volunteer or otherwise) that I have ever witnessed — hundreds of total strangers marshaling incredible competence with utter diligence and historic consequences for no reward. I wish I could have done more.

data.Name: Amber Leigh Turner
data.Short_bio: Amber Leigh Turner is a self-employed graphic and web designer for over 14 years. Frustrated with the lack of reliable COVID-19 data for Tennessee at the start of the pandemic, she started collecting Tennesee's data in her own spreadsheet. Eventually, she connected with The COVID Tracking Project to help provide even more data about Tennessee as well as participate in data entry, helping to make Tennessee's data more complete.

data.Name: Aliya Uteuova
data.Short_bio: I am a visual reporter covering environmental justice at the Guardian US. At the COVID Tracking project I've been a part of the Long-Term-Care Data team for the past 10 months. This project gave me an opportunity to be a part of something meaningful. It taught me patience and humility to document what happened to people.

data.Name: S.K. (Kayleigh) Van Poolen
data.Short_bio:
I came to The COVID Tracking Project with degrees in accounting, political science, urban planning, law with an emphasis on public interest law, information science, and academic work in educational and instructional technology. Some of my research explores First Amendment rights, social movements, and their web presence, collaborative learning spaces, data visualization principles, community-university partnerships, education policy, and public interest law curricula in law schools.  My interests extend to non-profit organizations' efforts related to civil rights, food insecurity, community resilience, experiential learning, including celebrations of community and culture. I am an advocate and creative force striving to be a part of a solution-building community, which is how I landed at CTP.

CTP’s effort to collect city data intrigued me and that is where I first started contributing. Then I spent substantial time working on a timeline project. I moved into data collection for our state data daily publication and the weekly Long-Term Care Data Tracker projects. In addition, I supported the collection of racial, age, gender, and comorbidities data for multiple states for The COVID Racial Data Tracker projects. Whenever possible, I assisted with various projects for Data Quality and community efforts such as the CTP History Project. Also, I have been known on occasion to provide comic relief, intentional or inadvertent.

data.Name: Chris von Csefalvay
data.Short_bio: A data scientist by background, I have been serving as the Vice-President of Special Projects at Starschema and responsible for our healthcare portfolio that includes insurers, life sciences/pharmaceutical companies, hospitals and health authorities. It has been a privilege to bring Starschema's ethos of using the transformative power of data science and data engineering for the common good by participating in the COVID Tracking Project.

data.Name: Neesha Wadhwa
data.Short_bio: I'm a UX Designer & Product Manager with nearly a decade of experience working with tech startups in Silicon Valley. In April 2020, I joined The COVID Tracking Project as a data and design volunteer. Soon afterwards, I became a Product Lead and managed website projects for the Racial Data Tracker.

data.Name: Peter Walker
data.Short_bio:
I'm a data viz enthusiast generally, Tableau aficionado specifically, and damn proud of the work we all did together at CTP.

Currently digging into the what, why, who, and how of private company equity at Carta.

data.Name: Laura S Welch
data.Short_bio: Laura is a CPA and independent healthcare decision support consultant with a passion for data. After growing up in Boston and spending 25+ years in CA, she now lives Phoenix, AZ. She is an avid Boston sports fan and more than casual foodie who also enjoys nature photography, reading, learning the piano, and whale-watching.

data.Name: Derek J. Wingert, PMP, CBAP
data.Short_bio: Derek is a Senior IT Project Manager and Analyst with a love of data and well-communicated information. Within The COVID Tracking Project, he helped with data efforts and standardizing annotations. Tangential to the project, Derek helped multiple states strategize their testing efforts and assisted Southern Minnesota in visualizing and communicating county-and community-level COVID trends.

data.Name: Ines Wingert
data.Short_bio: Ines is a marketing, communications, and PR professional with a long history at cause-based, mission-driven organizations. Her work at CTP involved community documentation, guides, and work instructions to better organize the amazing and sprawling community within the project. In her nonexistent spare time, Ines enjoys travel, kayaking, reading, and her household animals (a husband, two kids, cat, and lots of local wildlife).

data.Name: Nicole Wood
data.Short_bio: For almost 2 decades, I've worked in theatre and live events, specializing in "edutainment." As a creative producer and project manager, I spent about equal amounts of time on the art and the numbers. I joined CTP in November 2020, and I especially loved my shifts with the Data Entry team. Whether the numbers were going up or down, it was rewarding to be a part of tracking this important information.

data.Name: Marta Wosinska
data.Short_bio: Marta Wosińska, PhD, is the Deputy Director for Policy and Consulting Professor at the Duke-Margolis Center for Health Policy, Duke University.

data.Name: Nadia Zonis
data.Short_bio: I've worked as an editor, writer, researcher, and producer in NYC. I have graduate degrees in journalism from CUNY and in Modern European History from Columbia. CTP was a singular and cherished opportunity.

data.Name: Hannah Zook
data.Short_bio: I am a high school student at the Academy of Science in Loudoun County, Virginia. I also take college level courses in GIS and Computer Science at Northern Virginia Community College. I have been interested in science and technology since a very young age.  I think it is the only way to improve the world and the environment we live in if used correctly.  We can also improve the quality of life for people with disabilities which is a great interest of mine.  I also participate in the Maker Faire NoVa to show attendees how to use GIS in humanitarian causes. In my free time, I like to read, and I do competitive rock wall climbing.
